# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: automotive-ethernet
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] IEEE 802.1Qat and 802.1Qav amendments have been incorporated to the base IEEE 802.1Q-2011 document, which specifies the operation of Media Access Control (MAC) Bridges and Virtual Bridged Local Area Networks.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] AVB was initially developed by the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) Audio Video Bridging task group of the IEEE 802.1 standards committee.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] In November 2012, Audio Video Bridging task group was renamed to Time-Sensitive Networking task group to reflect the expanded scope of its work, which is to "provide the specifications that will allow time-synchronized low latency streaming services through IEEE 802 networks".
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] Further standardization efforts are ongoing in IEEE 802.1 TSN task group.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] To help ensure interoperability between devices that implement the AVB and TSN standards, the AVnu Alliance develops device certification for the automotive, consumer, and professional audio and video markets.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] Analog audio-video (AV) equipment historically used one-way, single-purpose, point-to-point connections.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] Even digital AV standards, such as S/PDIF for audio and the serial digital interface (SDI) for video, retain these properties.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] This connection model results in large masses of cables, especially in professional applications and high-end audio.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] Attempts to solve these problems were based on multi-point network topologies, such as IEEE 1394 (FireWire), and included adaptation of standard switched computer network technologies such as Audio over Ethernet and Audio over IP.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] Professional, home, and automotive AV solutions came to use specialized protocols that do not interoperate with each other or standard IT protocols, while standard computer networks did not provide tight quality of service with strict timing and predictable or bounded latency.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] To overcome these limitations, Audio Video Bridging networks transmit multiple audiovisual streams through standard Ethernet switches (i.e.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] *MAC bridges*) connected in a hierarchical tree topology.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] AVB includes layer 2 protocols to reserve connection bandwidth and prioritise network traffic, which guarantee precise sync clock and low transmission latency for each stream.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] Worst-case delay, including source and destination buffering, is required to be low and deterministic: the user-interface delay shall be around 50 ms, so that the pressing of a button and the resulting action are perceived as happening instantly, and 2 ms for live performance or studio work.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] Audio Video Bridging is implemented as a switched Ethernet network that works by reserving a fraction of the available Ethernet for AV traffic.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] The IEEE 802.1BA is an umbrella standard for these three principal technologies, which defines application-specific configurations and operation procedures for devices in switched audio-video networks.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] AVB traffic is replicated in a multicast manner, with one talker (stream initiator) and multiple listeners.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] AVB packets are sent at regular intervals in the allocated time slots, preventing collisions for AV traffic.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] AVB guarantees a latency of 2 ms for Class A traffic and 50 ms for Class B traffic over a maximum of 7 hops, with a transmission period of 125 μs for Class A and 250 μs for Class B traffic.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] An IEEE 802.1AS network timing domain includes all devices that communicate using the gPTP protocol.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] The grandmaster is a device chosen as the reference clock; the 802.1BA specification requires every talker and network bridge to be grandmaster capable.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] 802.3 link management and 802.1AS link delay measurement protocols calculate the round-trip delay to the AVB endpoint; this needs to be better than worst-case wire delay from the 802.1AS peer delay algorithm.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] Higher-level protocols may use 802.1AS clock information to set the exact presentation time for each AV stream.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] IEEE Std 1722-2011 for a Layer 2 Audio Video Transport Protocol (AVTP) defines details for transmitting IEEE 1394/IEC 61883 streams and other AV formats, setting the presentation time for each AV stream, and manage latencies from worst case delay calculated by the gPTP protocol.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] IEEE Std 1722.1-2013 is a standard that provides AVB discovery, enumeration, connection management, and control (AVDECC) of devices using IEEE Std 1722-2011.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] AVDECC defines operations to discover device addition and removal, retrieve device entity model, connect and disconnect streams, manage device and connection status, and remote control devices.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] Higher-layer services can improve synchronisation and latency of media transmission by mapping the AVB Stream ID to internal stream identifiers and basing internal timestamps on gPTP master clock.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] AES67 is based on standard RTP over UDP/IP and IEEE 1588 Precision Time Protocol (PTPv2) for timing; interoperability with AVB/TSN can be achieved by linking IEEE 802.1AS timing information to AES67 PTPv2 payload data.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] AES67 implementation with AVB interoperability has been demoed at InfoComm 2016.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] In 2018, the Avnu Alliance announced the Milan initiative to promote interoperability of AVB devices and provide product certification and testing.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] Redundancy is provided with two independent logical networks for every endpoint and a seamless switchover mechanism.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] The IETF Deterministic Networking (DetNet) Working Group is working to define deterministic data paths with bounds on latency, loss, and packet delay variation (jitter), and high reliability.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] DetNet shall operate over both Layer 2 bridged segments and Layer 3 routed segments, relying on interoperability with AVB/TSN switches when possible.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] The stated goal is to enable geographically distributed, campus- or enterprise-wide Intranet for content delivery with bounded low latency (10-15 ms).
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] A single network shall handle both A/V and IT traffic, with Layer 3 routing on top of AVB QoS networks to enable sharing content between Layer 2 AVB segments, and provide IntServ and DiffServ integration with AVB where possible.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] Unused reserved bandwidth shall be released for best-effort traffic.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] The protocol stack shall have Plug-and-play capabilities from top to bottom to reduce manual setup and administration, allow quick changes of network devices and network topology.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] The work on A/V streaming started at the IEEE 802.3re 'Residential Ethernet' study group in July 2004.
[src:automotive-ethernet/audio-video-bridging] In November 2005, it was moved to the IEEE 802.1 committee responsible for cross-network bridging standards.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] These standards are specified in Clauses 125 and 126 of the IEEE 802.3 standard.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] The physical (PHY) layer transmission technology of IEEE 802.3bz is based on 10GBASE-T, but operates at a lower signaling rate.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] By reducing the original signal rate to 1⁄4 or 1⁄2, the link speed drops to 2.5 or 5 Gbit/s, respectively.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] The spectral bandwidth of the signal is reduced accordingly, lowering the requirements on the cabling, so that 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T can be deployed at a cable length of up to 100 m on Cat 5e or better cables.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] The NBASE-T effort also standardized how its switches can implement power over Ethernet according to the IEEE 802.3at and successor standards.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] This allows a single cable to provide both power and data for high-bandwidth wireless access points such as those that implement the IEEE 802.11ax (Wi-Fi 6) and IEEE 802.11be (Wi-Fi 7) standards.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] Prior to the release of 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T, manufacturers of wireless access points that wanted to support multi-gigabit uplink speed using standard gigabit Ethernet ports had to include multiple Ethernet ports on their access points.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] By bonding the connections from multiple Ethernet ports via IEEE 802.3ad link aggregation or similar, manufacturers were able to achieve speeds close to 2 Gbit/s by using two ports that support gigabit speeds.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] This would require the wireless access point to be connected to the rest of the network with 2 Ethernet cables and require both the wireless access point and network hardware to support and be configured for link aggregation.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] Wireless access points that support 2.5GBASE-T or 5GBASE-T eliminate this complexity.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] In 2013 with the release of IEEE 802.11ac (Wi-Fi 5), wireless access points for the first time could reach speeds of 2 Gbit/s or 4 Gbit/s, exceeding the 1 Gbit/s IEEE 802.3ab 1000BASE-T wired Ethernet uplink.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] While 10GBASE-T had already been standardized since 2006, this standard used a higher signaling frequency that would have substantially limited the maximum distance of Cat5e cable runs.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] Therefore, there was demand for an intermediate standard that could uplink the 2 Gbit/s and 4 Gbit/s speeds from wireless access points over existing Cat5e cable.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] The development of the 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T standards enabled wireless access points to reach their maximum speeds without being limited by the Ethernet uplink speeds over a single existing Cat5e cable, while also being compatible with newer Cat6 and Cat6a cabling.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] The 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T standards also serve as an interim solution for achieving lower-cost and lower power consumption multi-gigabit network speeds.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] As of Dec 2022, 10GBASE-T network equipment is still substantially more expensive than 1GBASE-T, 2.5GBASE-T, and 5GBASE-T network equipment.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] IEEE 802.3bz also supports power over Ethernet, which had previously not been available with IEEE 802.3an 10GBASE-T.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] As early as 2013, the Intel Avoton server processors integrated 2.5 Gbit/s Ethernet ports.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] Whilst Broadcom had announced a series of 2.5 Gbit/s transceiver ICs, 2.5 Gbit/s switch hardware was not widely commercially available at that point.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] Many early 10GBASE-T switches, particularly those with SFP+ interfaces, do not support the intermediate speeds.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] In October 2014, the NBASE-T Alliance was founded, initially comprising Cisco, Aquantia, Freescale, and Xilinx.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] By December 2015, it contained more than 45 companies, and aimed to have its specification compatible with 802.3bz.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] The competing MGBASE-T Alliance, stating the same faster Gigabit Ethernet objectives, was founded in December 2014.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] In contrast to NBASE-T, the MGBASE-T said that their specifications would be open source.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] IEEE 802.3's 2.5G/5GBASE-T Task Force started working on the 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T standards in March 2015.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] The two NBASE-T and MGBASE-T Alliances ended up collaborating. with the forming of the IEEE 802.3bz Task Force under the patronage of the Ethernet Alliance in June 2015.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] On September 23, 2016, the IEEE-SA Standards Board approved IEEE Std 802.3bz-2016.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] The IEEE 802.3ch-2020 2.5GBASE-T1, 5GBASE-T1, and 10GBASE-T1 standards are derived from the IEEE 802.3bp-2016 1000BASE-T1 Ethernet over single twisted pair standard, and share very little in common with the similarly named 2.5GBASE-T and 5GBASE-T standards at the PHY layer.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] 2.5GBASE-T1, 5GBASE-T1, and 10GBASE-T1 can run over a single twisted pair up to 15 meters in length, use PAM8 modulation (compared to PAM3 modulation in 1000BASE-T1 or PAM-16 + 128DSQ in 2.5GBASE-T/5GBASE-T), and are standardized in 802.3ch-2020.
[src:automotive-ethernet/automotive-ethernet] Their primary use is in embedded automotive applications, and are commonly referred to as part of the Automotive Ethernet family of standards, along with 100BASE-T1 and 1000BASE-T1.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Ethernet has since been refined to support higher bit rates, a greater number of nodes, and longer link distances, but retains much backward compatibility.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Over time, Ethernet has largely replaced competing wired LAN technologies such as Token Ring, FDDI and ARCNET.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The original 10BASE5 Ethernet uses a thick coaxial cable as a shared medium.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Its immediate successor 10BASE2 uses a thinner and more flexible cable that is both less expensive and easier to use.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] More modern Ethernet variants use twisted pair and fiber optic links in conjunction with switches.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Over the course of its history, Ethernet data transfer rates have been increased from the original 2.94 Mbit/s to the latest 800 Gbit/s, with rates up to 1.6 Tbit/s under development.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The Ethernet standards include several wiring and signaling variants of the OSI physical layer.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Systems communicating over Ethernet divide a stream of data into shorter pieces called frames.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Each frame contains source and destination addresses, and error-checking data so that damaged frames can be detected and discarded; most often, higher-layer protocols trigger retransmission of lost frames.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Per the OSI model, Ethernet provides services up to and including the data link layer.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The 48-bit MAC address was adopted by other IEEE 802 networking standards, including IEEE 802.11 (Wi-Fi), as well as by FDDI.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] EtherType values are also used in Subnetwork Access Protocol (SNAP) headers.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Ethernet is widely used in homes and industry, and interworks well with wireless Wi-Fi technologies.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Ethernet commonly carries Internet Protocol traffic, and so Ethernet is considered one of the key technologies that make up the Internet.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The original forms of Ethernet used a shared communications channel.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] This concept originated in ALOHAnet, designed in the late 1960s by Norman Abramson.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] ALOHANet was a 4800 bps radio network used by the University of Hawaii.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] When a sender detected that its message hadn't been received, it would resend the message after waiting for a randomly selected period of time.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In 1972, Robert Metcalfe and David Boggs adapted the ALOHAnet approach to transmission over a shared coaxial cable in the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (Xerox PARC).
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] This network connected ALTO computers using a coaxial cable.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] It first ran on May 22, 1973 with a bit rate of 2.94 Mbps.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In a memo written at that time, Metcalfe named the concept "Ethernet." The name was inspired by the former idea that the universe was filled with a "luminiferous aether" that carried electromagnetic waves, and calling it Ethernet emphasized its ability to run over any transmission medium.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Ethernet improved the original ALOHANet design because a sender would first listen to the channel to determine if it was already in use.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The combination of the new idea of *Carrier Sense* with *Multiple Access* and *Collision Detection* from ALOHANet became Carrier-Sense Multiple Access/Collision Detection, or CSMA/CD.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In 1975, Metcalfe, Boggs and their colleagues Charles Thacker and Butler Lampson filed for a patent on Ethernet, which was granted in 1977.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] By 1976, 100 ALTOs at Xerox PARC were connected using Ethernet.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In July 1976, Metcalfe and Boggs published the seminal paper *Ethernet: Distributed Packet Switching for Local Computer Networks* in Communications of the ACM (CACM).
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Subsequently between 1976-1978 Ron Crane, Bob Garner, Hal Murray, and Roy Ogus designed a 10Mbps version of Ethernet running over coaxial cable.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] There were multiple local area network technologies in the 1970s.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] These included IBM's Token Ring, Network Systems Corporation's HYPERchannel and Datapoint's ARCnet.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Version 2 was published in November 1982.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In June 1981, the Institute of Electronic and Electrical Engineers (IEEE) Project 802 (for local area network standards) created an 802.3 subcommittee to produce an Ethernet standard based on DIX.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In 1983, a standard was published for 10 Mbps Ethernet over a coaxial cable of up to 500 meters (10BASE5).
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] It differed only in some details from the DIX standard.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] As part of the standardization process, Xerox turned over all its Ethernet patents to the IEEE, and anyone can implement 802.3.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] IEEE 802.3 is now considered the same as Ethernet.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The cooperation of Xerox with Intel and Digital on the Ethernet standard ultimately made it a truly open standard.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In June 1979, Metcalfe left Xerox to found the Computer, Communication, and Compatibility Corporation, better known as 3Com, along with Howard Charney, Ron Crane, Greg Shaw, and Bill Krause.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Metcalfe's vision was to sell Ethernet adapters for all personal computers.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Apple quickly agreed, but IBM was committed to their own LAN protocol, the Token Ring.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Nonetheless, 3Com developed the EtherLink ISA adapter and started shipping it with DOS driver software, making it usable on IBM PCs.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The EtherLink adapter had several advantages over competitors.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] It was the first network interface card (NIC) to use VLSI semiconductor technology (developed in partnership with Seeq Technologies).
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] This meant most of the functions, including the transceiver, could be contained on a single chip, so the price for Etherlink ($950) was significantly lower than of its competitors.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] 3Com introduced a new, thinner coaxial cable for the card, called Thin Ethernet, making it more convenient to install and use.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Finally, Etherlink was the first Ethernet adapter for the IBM PC.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Because both businesses and home users adopted the IBM PC, its market expanded rapidly, and by 1982, IBM was shipping 200,000 units a month.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Since IBM hadn't realized that businesses would want the computers connected by a network, Etherlink sales filled the vacuum, and in 1984, 3Com was able to file for a public stock offering.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The Etherlink approach was standardized by IEEE as 10BASE2 in 1984.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Also in the early 1980s, Novell began selling Network Interface Cards (NICs) to go with its NetWare operating system.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] These NE2000 NICs were all Ethernet, and because NetWare became an important application for businesses, this increased the demand for Ethernet adapters.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Then in 1989, Novell sold its NIC business and licensed the NE2000 card, creating a highly competitive market and driving the price of Ethernet cards down, while cards for other technologies, such as IBM's Token Ring, remained high.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Starting in late 1983, AT&T and NCR promoted a star configuration using unshielded twisted pair cabling (UTP), or regular telephone wire.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] This became StarLAN, running at 1Mbps over cables up to 500 meters, and was standardized as 1BASE5 by IEEE 802.3, but on August 17, 1987, SynOptics introduced LATTISNET with 10Mbps Ethernet also over regular telephone wire (UTP).
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In the fall of 1990, the IEEE issued the 802.3i standard for 10BASE-T, Ethernet over twisted pairs, and the following year, Ethernet sales nearly doubled.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] By 1992, Ethernet was the de facto standard for LANs.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In the 1990s, the proliferation of PCs combined with their increasing power drove demand for much faster network infrastructure.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The Kalpana EtherSwitch EPS-700 helped to meet this demand by increasing the speed of Ethernet dramatically.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The switch allowed multiple simultaneous data transmission paths and it used faster cut-through bridging technology in place of store-and-forward.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The switch was marketed as a way to improve network performance rather than as a way to connect different LANs, creating a new market category.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Then in 1993, Kalpana introduced full-duplex mode for switches, potentially doubling the data transmission rate.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In 1997, the IEEE standardized full-duplex flow-control switched in 802.3x.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The 10Mbps rate of Ethernet was still too slow for some networks, though, and most larger networks planned to use FDDI, a very expensive alternative to Ethernet.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In August 1991 Howard Charney, David Boggs, Ron Crane, and Larry Birenbaum founded Grand Junction Networks to build and market 100Mbps Ethernet equipment.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Their announcement in 1992 triggered a standards war over whether to maintain backward compatibility with the original Ethernet CSMA/CD standard or to adopt a demand-priority protocol pushed by HP and AT&T.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Since the competing groups were unable to come to an agreement, IEEE set up a new group, 802.12, for the demand-priority scheme.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The supporters of backward compatibility formed the Fast Ethernet Alliance in 1993 to publish an interoperability specification that became the 100BASE-TX standard (also known as Fast Ethernet).
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] At the same time, Grand Junction shipped the first Fast Ethernet hubs and NICs, and more companies announced Fast Ethernet equipment.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In 1994, Sun Microsystems, followed by 3Com, DEC, and others, shipped 100BASE-TX compliant products, and the IEEE 802.3u specification for Fast Ethernet was approved.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Since 1999, Ethernet's maximum speed has increased with the introductions of Gigabit Ethernet (802.3ab), 2.5 and 5 Gbit/s Ethernet (802.3bz), 10 Gigabit Ethernet (802.3ae), 25 Gigabit Ethernet (802.3by), 50 Gigabit Ethernet (802.3cd), 100 Gigabit Ethernet (802.3ba), and Terabit Ethernet (802.3df).
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In February 1980, the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) started project 802 to standardize local area networks (LAN).
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The DIX group with Gary Robinson (DEC), Phil Arst (Intel), and Bob Printis (Xerox) submitted the so-called *Blue Book* CSMA/CD specification as a candidate for the LAN specification.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In addition to CSMA/CD, Token Ring (supported by IBM) and Token Bus (selected and henceforward supported by General Motors) were also considered as candidates for a LAN standard.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Competing proposals and broad interest in the initiative led to strong disagreement over which technology to standardize.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In December 1980, the group was split into three subgroups, and standardization proceeded separately for each proposal.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The development of the CSMA/CD standard was slowed by conflict over issues such as baseband versus broadband and the lengths of address fields.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Some members of the DIX group became impatient with the process and concerned that the ultimate CSMA/CD standard would differ significantly from their "Blue Book" de facto standard.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] They turned instead to the European Computer Manufacturers Association (ECMA), where Friedrich Röscheisen of Siemens helped to introduce the Blue Book as a candidate standard to a newly created "Local Networks" Task Group (TC24).
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Gary Robinson later claimed to have instigated the effort to convince ECMA to standardize CSMA/CD.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] ECMA approved a standard in June 1982 that was very close to the DIX de facto standard.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Because the DIX proposal was the most technically complete and because of the speedy action taken by ECMA, the IEEE group felt compelled to approve the 802.3 CSMA/CD standard in December 1982.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] It differed only slightly from the DIX standard in terminology and frame format.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] IEEE published the 802.3 standard as a draft in 1983 and as a standard in 1985.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The ISO 8802-3 standard was published on March 23, 1989.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The IEEE has approved changes to its 802.3 (Ethernet) standard regularly since 1985.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The current standard is available from the IEEE website.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] With each change to the standard, the IEEE first issues a supplement with a letter designation added to IEEE 802.3.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] For example, IEEE 802.3u refers to Fast Ethernet.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Then when the supplement is formally approved, it is merged with the main standard.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Subsequent standards have provided for ever-faster versions of Ethernet, additional physical media, and network management.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] For a table of IEEE Ethernet standards, see IEEE 802.3 § Communication standards.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Ethernet has evolved to include higher bandwidth, improved medium access control methods, and different physical media.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The multidrop coaxial cable was replaced with physical point-to-point links connected by Ethernet repeaters or switches.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Ethernet stations communicate by sending each other data packets: blocks of data individually sent and delivered.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] As with other IEEE 802 LANs, each adapter comes programmed with a globally unique 48-bit MAC address so that each Ethernet station has a unique address.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The MAC addresses are used to specify both the destination and the source of each data packet.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Ethernet establishes link-level connections, which can be defined using both the destination and source addresses.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] On reception of a transmission, the receiver uses the destination address to determine whether the transmission is relevant to the station or should be ignored.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] A network interface normally does not accept packets addressed to other Ethernet stations.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] An EtherType field in each frame is used by the operating system on the receiving station to select the appropriate protocol module (e.g., an Internet Protocol version such as IPv4).
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Ethernet frames are said to be *self-identifying*, because of the EtherType field.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Self-identifying frames make it possible to intermix multiple protocols on the same physical network and allow a single computer to use multiple protocols together.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Despite the evolution of Ethernet technology, all generations of Ethernet (excluding early experimental versions) use the same frame formats.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Mixed-speed networks can be built using Ethernet switches and repeaters supporting the desired Ethernet variants.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Due to the ubiquity of Ethernet and the ever-decreasing cost of the hardware needed to support it, by 2004 most manufacturers built Ethernet interfaces directly into PC motherboards, eliminating the need for a separate network card.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Ethernet was originally based on the idea of computers communicating over a shared coaxial cable acting as a broadcast transmission medium.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The method used was similar to those used in radio systems, with the common cable providing the communication channel likened to the *Luminiferous aether* in 19th-century physics, and it was from this reference that the name *Ethernet* was derived.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The original Ethernet's shared coaxial cable (the shared medium) traversed a building or campus to connect every attached machine.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] A scheme known as carrier-sense multiple access with collision detection (CSMA/CD) governed the way the computers shared the channel.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] This scheme was simpler than competing Token Ring or Token Bus technologies.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Computers are connected to an Attachment Unit Interface (AUI) transceiver, which is in turn connected to the cable (with thin Ethernet, the transceiver is usually integrated into the network adapter).
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] While a simple passive wire is highly reliable for small networks, it is not reliable for large extended networks, where damage to the wire in a single place, or a single bad connector, can make the whole Ethernet segment unusable.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Through the first half of the 1980s, Ethernet's 10BASE5 implementation utilised a coaxial cable 0.375 inches (9.5 mm) in diameter, later referred to as *thick Ethernet* or *thicknet*.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Its successor, 10BASE2, called *thin Ethernet* or *thinnet*, used the RG-58 coaxial cable.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The emphasis was on making installation of the cable easier and less costly.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Since all communication happens on the same wire, any information sent by one computer is received by all, even if that information is intended for just one destination.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The network interface card interrupts the CPU only when applicable packets are received: the card ignores information not addressed to it.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Use of a single cable also means that the data bandwidth is shared, such that, for example, available data bandwidth to each device is halved when two stations are simultaneously active.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] A collision happens when two stations attempt to transmit at the same time.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] They corrupt transmitted data and require stations to re-transmit.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The loss of data and retransmission reduce throughput.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In the worst case, where multiple active hosts connected with maximum allowed cable length attempt to transmit many short frames, excessive collisions can reduce throughput dramatically.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] However, a Xerox report in 1980, published in Communications of the ACM, studied the performance of an existing Ethernet installation under both normal and artificially generated heavy load.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The report claimed that 98% throughput on the LAN was observed.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] This is in contrast with token passing LANs (Token Ring, Token Bus), all of which suffer throughput degradation as each new node comes into the LAN, due to token waits.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] This report was controversial, as modeling showed that collision-based networks theoretically became unstable under loads as low as 37% of nominal capacity.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Many early researchers failed to understand these results.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Performance on real networks is significantly better.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In a modern Ethernet, the stations do not all share one channel through a shared cable or a simple repeater hub; instead, each station communicates with a switch, which in turn forwards that traffic to the destination station.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In this topology, collisions are only possible if the station and switch attempt to communicate with each other at the same time, and collisions are limited to this link.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Furthermore, the 10BASE-T standard introduced a full duplex mode of operation, which became familiar with Fast Ethernet and the de facto standard with Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In full duplex, a switch and a station can send and receive simultaneously, and therefore modern Ethernet networks are completely collision-free.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] For signal degradation and timing reasons, coaxial Ethernet segments have a restricted size.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Somewhat larger networks can be built by using an Ethernet repeater.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Early repeaters had only two ports, allowing, at most, a doubling of network size.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Once repeaters with more than two ports became available, it was possible to wire the network in a star topology.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Early experiments with star topologies (called *Fibernet*) using optical fiber were published by 1978.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Shared cable Ethernet is always hard to install in offices because its bus topology is in conflict with the star topology cable plans designed into buildings for telephony.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Modifying Ethernet to conform to twisted-pair telephone wiring already installed in commercial buildings provided another opportunity to lower costs, expand the installed base, and leverage building design, and, thus, twisted-pair Ethernet was the next logical development in the mid-1980s.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Ethernet on unshielded twisted-pair cables (UTP) began with StarLAN at 1 Mbit/s in the mid-1980s.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In 1987 SynOptics introduced the first twisted-pair Ethernet at 10 Mbit/s in a star-wired cabling topology with a central hub, later called LattisNet.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] These evolved into 10BASE-T, which was designed for point-to-point links only, and all termination was built into the device.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] This changed repeaters from a specialist device used at the center of large networks to a device that every twisted pair-based network with more than two machines had to use.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The tree structure that resulted from this made Ethernet networks easier to maintain by preventing most faults with one peer or its associated cable from affecting other devices on the network.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Every packet is sent to every other port on the repeater, so bandwidth and security problems are not addressed.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The total throughput of the repeater is limited to that of a single link, and all links must operate at the same speed.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] While repeaters can isolate some aspects of Ethernet segments, such as cable breakages, they still forward all traffic to all Ethernet devices.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The entire network is one collision domain, and all hosts have to be able to detect collisions anywhere on the network.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] This limits the number of repeaters between the farthest nodes and creates practical limits on how many machines can communicate on an Ethernet network.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Segments joined by repeaters have to all operate at the same speed, making phased-in upgrades impossible.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] To alleviate these problems, bridging was created to communicate at the data link layer while isolating the physical layer.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] With bridging, only well-formed Ethernet packets are forwarded from one Ethernet segment to another; collisions and packet errors are isolated.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] At initial startup, Ethernet bridges work somewhat like Ethernet repeaters, passing all traffic between segments.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] By observing the source addresses of incoming frames, the bridge then builds an address table associating addresses to segments.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Once an address is learned, the bridge forwards network traffic destined for that address only to the associated segment, improving overall performance.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Broadcast traffic is still forwarded to all network segments.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Bridges also overcome the limits on total segments between two hosts and allow the mixing of speeds, both of which are critical to the incremental deployment of faster Ethernet variants.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In 1989, Motorola Codex introduced their 6310 EtherSpan, and Kalpana introduced their EtherSwitch; these were examples of the first commercial Ethernet switches.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Early switches such as this used cut-through switching where only the header of the incoming packet is examined before it is either dropped or forwarded to another segment.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] One drawback of this method is that it does not readily allow a mixture of different link speeds.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Another is that packets that have been corrupted are still propagated through the network.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The eventual remedy for this was a return to the original store and forward approach of bridging, where the packet is read into a buffer on the switch in its entirety, its frame check sequence verified and only then the packet is forwarded.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In modern network equipment, this process is typically done using application-specific integrated circuits allowing packets to be forwarded at wire speed.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] When a twisted pair or fiber link segment is used, and neither end is connected to a repeater, full-duplex Ethernet becomes possible over that segment.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In full-duplex mode, both devices can transmit and receive to and from each other at the same time, and there is no collision domain.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] This doubles the aggregate bandwidth of the link and is sometimes advertised as double the link speed (for example, 200 Mbit/s for Fast Ethernet).
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The elimination of the collision domain for these connections also means that all the link's bandwidth can be used by the two devices on that segment and that segment length is not limited by the constraints of collision detection.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Since packets are typically delivered only to the port they are intended for, traffic on a switched Ethernet is less public than on shared-medium Ethernet.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Despite this, switched Ethernet should still be regarded as an insecure network technology, because it is easy to subvert switched Ethernet systems by means such as ARP spoofing and MAC flooding.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The bandwidth advantages, the improved isolation of devices from each other, the ability to easily mix different speeds of devices and the elimination of the chaining limits inherent in non-switched Ethernet have made switched Ethernet the dominant network technology.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Advanced networking features in switches use Shortest Path Bridging (SPB) or the Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) to maintain a loop-free, meshed network, allowing physical loops for redundancy (STP) or load-balancing (SPB).
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Shortest Path Bridging includes the use of the link-state routing protocol IS-IS to allow larger networks with shortest path routes between devices.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In 2016, Ethernet replaced InfiniBand as the most popular system interconnect of TOP500 supercomputers.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In many industrial systems, Ethernet and fieldbus coexist, each performing certain roles, and data is exchanged between them through gateways.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The Ethernet physical layer evolved over a considerable time span and encompasses coaxial, twisted pair and fiber-optic physical media interfaces, with speeds from 1 Mbit/s to 400 Gbit/s.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The first introduction of twisted-pair CSMA/CD was StarLAN, standardized as 802.3 1BASE5.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] While 1BASE5 had little market penetration, it defined the physical apparatus (wire, plug/jack, pin-out, and wiring plan) that would be carried over to 10BASE-T through 10GBASE-T.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The most common forms used are 10BASE-T, 100BASE-TX, and 1000BASE-T.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] All three use twisted-pair cables and 8P8C modular connectors.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] They run at 10 Mbit/s, 100 Mbit/s, and 1 Gbit/s, respectively.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Fiber optic variants of Ethernet (that commonly use SFP modules) are also very popular in larger networks, offering high performance, better electrical isolation and longer distance (tens of kilometers with some versions).
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In general, network protocol stack software will work similarly on all varieties.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] In IEEE 802.3, a datagram is called a packet or frame.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] *Packet* is used to describe the overall transmission unit and includes the preamble, start frame delimiter (SFD) and carrier extension (if present).
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The *frame* begins after the start frame delimiter with a frame header featuring source and destination MAC addresses and the EtherType field giving either the protocol type for the payload protocol or the length of the payload.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The middle section of the frame consists of payload data, including any headers for other protocols (for example, Internet Protocol) carried in the frame.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The frame ends with a 32-bit cyclic redundancy check, which is used to detect corruption of data in transit.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Notably, Ethernet packets have no time-to-live field, leading to possible problems in the presence of a switching loop.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Autonegotiation is the procedure by which two connected devices choose common transmission parameters, e.g., speed and duplex mode.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Autonegotiation was initially an optional feature, first introduced with 100BASE-TX (1995 IEEE 802.3u Fast Ethernet standard), and is backward compatible with 10BASE-T.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The specification was improved in the 1998 release of IEEE 802.3.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Autonegotiation is mandatory for 1000BASE-T and faster.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] A switching loop or bridge loop occurs in computer networks when there is more than one Layer 2 (OSI model) path between two endpoints (e.g., multiple connections between two network switches or two ports on the same switch connected to each other).
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The loop creates broadcast storms as broadcasts and multicasts are forwarded by switches out every port, the switch or switches will repeatedly rebroadcast the broadcast messages flooding the network.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Since the Layer 2 header does not support a *time to live* (TTL) value, if a frame is sent into a looped topology, it can loop forever.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] A physical topology that contains switching or bridge loops is attractive for redundancy reasons, yet a switched network must not have loops.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] The solution is to allow physical loops, but create a loop-free logical topology using the SPB protocol or the older STP on the network switches.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] A node that is sending longer than the maximum transmission window for an Ethernet packet is considered to be *jabbering*.
[src:automotive-ethernet/ethernet] Depending on the physical topology, jabber detection and remedy differ somewhat.
[src:automotive-ethernet/in-vehicle-infotainment] Driven by the demand for more connected vehicles, in-car entertainment is getting more and more sophisticated.
[src:automotive-ethernet/in-vehicle-infotainment] Car makers, electronics and software suppliers, as well as newcomers from the Silicon Valley (such as Google and Apple), work together and also compete to come up with infotainment systems that are user-friendly and safe to use.
[src:automotive-ethernet/in-vehicle-infotainment] ICE systems are increasingly commonplace with newer vehicle models and several auto makers have developed their own systems: Ford with SYNC and MyFord Touch, Toyota with Entune, Cadillac with CUE (Cadillac User Experience), FCA with Uconnect, etc.
[src:automotive-ethernet/in-vehicle-infotainment] With the mass adoption of smartphones worldwide, a new issue has emerged: the use of connected devices in the car.
[src:automotive-ethernet/in-vehicle-infotainment] According to a 2015 survey conducted by AT&T with a sample of over 2,000 US respondents, "7-in-10 people engage in smartphone activities while driving" including social media (40%), web browsing (30%) and even video chatting (10%).
[src:automotive-ethernet/in-vehicle-infotainment] This raises safety concerns related to distracted driving and also pushes the automotive industry to integrate those devices in a safe manner.
[src:automotive-ethernet/in-vehicle-infotainment] "Traditional" car makers increasingly rely on the software and electronics expertise of auto suppliers and technology companies to help them design such systems.
[src:automotive-ethernet/in-vehicle-infotainment] Policies regarding in-car entertainment systems are less developed than cell phone usage laws regarding similar distractions in cars.
[src:automotive-ethernet/in-vehicle-infotainment] Domestic rules for Telecom-, data protection and lawful access can be applicable, but the legal environment is diverse and different for each country.
[src:automotive-ethernet/in-vehicle-infotainment] In the United States, 10 states, D.C., Guam, and the Virgin Islands prohibit all drivers from using handheld cell phones while driving.
[src:automotive-ethernet/in-vehicle-infotainment] Additionally, 39 states, D.C., Guam, and the Virgin Islands ban text messaging for all drivers.
[src:automotive-ethernet/in-vehicle-infotainment] However, few states have developed laws to limit the content that drivers can view on in-car entertainment systems.
[src:automotive-ethernet/in-vehicle-infotainment] Still, researchers are beginning to analyze the potential impact of distracted drivers on the roads.
[src:automotive-ethernet/in-vehicle-infotainment] Charlie Klauer, a researcher at the Virginia Tech Transportation Institute, says that drivers who look at screens have a much higher risk of crashing.
[src:automotive-ethernet/in-vehicle-infotainment] Furthermore, the risk of crashing rises exponentially the longer a driver has taken their eyes off the road.
[src:automotive-ethernet/in-vehicle-infotainment] Automotive companies like Ford and Audi contend that they have tested and revised their latest systems in order to reduce the amount of time that drivers spend looking away from the road.
[src:automotive-ethernet/in-vehicle-infotainment] As car infotainment systems can access more and more functions of the vehicle (e.g. through the CAN bus), concerns have also been voiced about potential remote car hacking (see drive by wire).
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] In the seven-layer OSI model of computer networking, the **physical layer** or **layer 1** is the first and lowest layer: the layer most closely associated with the physical connection between devices.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] The physical layer provides an electrical, mechanical, and procedural interface to the transmission medium.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] The shapes and properties of the electrical connectors, the frequencies to transmit on, the line code to use and similar low-level parameters are specified by the physical layer.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] At the electrical layer, the physical layer is commonly implemented in a dedicated PHY chip or, in electronic design automation (EDA), by a design block.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] In mobile computing, the MIPI Alliance *-PHY family of interconnect protocols are widely used.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] The physical layer defines the means of transmitting a stream of raw bits over a physical data link connecting network nodes.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] The bitstream may be grouped into code words or symbols and converted to a physical signal that is transmitted over a transmission medium.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] The physical layer consists of the electronic circuit transmission technologies of a network.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] It is a fundamental layer underlying the higher level functions in a network, and can be implemented through a great number of different hardware technologies with widely varying characteristics.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] Within the semantics of the OSI model, the physical layer translates logical communications requests from the data link layer into hardware-specific operations to cause transmission or reception of electronic (or other) signals.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] The physical layer supports higher layers responsible for generation of logical data packets.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] The Internet protocol suite, as defined in RFC 1122 and RFC 1123, is a high-level networking description used for the Internet and similar networks.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] It does not define a layer that deals exclusively with hardware-level specifications and interfaces, as this model does not concern itself directly with physical interfaces.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] The major functions and services performed by the physical layer are: The physical layer performs bit-by-bit or symbol-by-symbol data delivery over a physical transmission medium.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] It provides a standardized interface to the transmission medium, including a mechanical specification of electrical connectors and cables, for example maximum cable length, an electrical specification of transmission line signal level and impedance.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] The physical layer is responsible for electromagnetic compatibility including electromagnetic spectrum frequency allocation and specification of signal strength, analog bandwidth, etc.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] The transmission medium may be electrical or optical over optical fiber or a wireless communication link such as free-space optical communication or radio.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] Line coding is used to convert data into a pattern of electrical fluctuations which may be modulated onto a carrier wave or infrared light.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] The flow of data is managed with bit synchronization in synchronous serial communication or start-stop signalling and flow control in asynchronous serial communication.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] Sharing of the transmission medium among multiple network participants can be handled by simple circuit switching or multiplexing.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] More complex medium access control protocols for sharing the transmission medium may use carrier sense and collision detection, such as in Ethernet's Carrier-sense multiple access with collision detection (CSMA/CD).
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] To optimize reliability and efficiency, signal processing techniques such as equalization, training sequences and pulse shaping may be used.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] Error correction codes and techniques including forward error correction may be applied to further improve reliability.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] A **PHY**, an abbreviation for *physical layer*, is an electronic circuit, usually implemented as an integrated circuit, required to implement physical layer functions of the OSI model in a network interface controller.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] A PHY connects a link layer device (often called MAC as an acronym for medium access control) to a physical medium such as an optical fiber or copper cable.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] A PHY device typically includes both physical coding sublayer (PCS) and physical medium dependent (PMD) layer functionality.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] Modular transceivers for fiber-optic communication (like the SFP family) complement a PHY chip and form the PMD sublayer.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] The **Ethernet PHY** is a component that operates at the physical layer of the OSI network model.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] It implements the physical layer portion of the Ethernet.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] Its purpose is to provide analog signal physical access to the link.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] It is usually interfaced with a media-independent interface (MII) to a MAC chip in a microcontroller or another system that takes care of the higher-layer functions.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] More specifically, the Ethernet PHY is a chip that implements the hardware send and receive function of Ethernet frames; it interfaces between the analog domain of Ethernet's line modulation and the digital domain of link-layer packet signaling.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] The PHY usually does not handle MAC addressing, as that is the link layer's job.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] Similarly, wake-on-LAN and boot ROM functionality is implemented in the network interface card (NIC), which may have PHY, MAC, and other functionality integrated into one chip or as separate chips.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] Common Ethernet interfaces include fiber or two to four copper pairs for data communication.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] However, there now exists a new interface, called Single Pair Ethernet (SPE), which is able to utilize a single pair of copper wires while still communicating at the intended speeds.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] Texas Instruments DP83TD510E is an example of a PHY which uses SPE.
[src:automotive-ethernet/physical-layer] Examples include the Microsemi SimpliPHY and SynchroPHY VSC82xx/84xx/85xx/86xx family, Marvell Alaska 88E1310/88E1310S/88E1318/88E1318S Gigabit Ethernet transceivers, Texas Instruments DP838xx family and offerings from Intel and ICS.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The majority of projects define extensions to the IEEE 802.1Q – Bridges and Bridged Networks, which describes virtual LANs and network switches.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] These extensions in particular address transmission with very low latency and high availability.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Applications include converged networks with real-time audio/video streaming and real-time control streams which are used in automotive applications and industrial control facilities.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Standard information technology network equipment has no concept of "time" and cannot provide synchronization and precision timing.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Delivering data reliably is more important than delivering within a specific time, so there are no constraints on delay or synchronization precision.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Even if the average hop delay is very low, individual delays can be unacceptably high.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Network congestion is handled by throttling and retransmitting dropped packets at the transport layer, but there are no means to prevent congestion at the link layer.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Data can be lost when the buffers are too small or the bandwidth is insufficient, but excessive buffering adds to the delay, which is unacceptable when low deterministic delays are required.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The different AVB/TSN standards documents specified by IEEE 802.1 can be grouped into three basic key component categories that are required for a complete real-time communication solution based on switched Ethernet networks with deterministic quality of service (QoS) for point-to-point connections.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Each and every standard specification can be used on its own and is mostly self-sufficient.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] However, only when used together in a concerted way, can TSN achieve its full potential as a communication system.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The IEEE AVB/TSN suite serves as the foundation for deterministic networking to satisfy the common requirements of these applications.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] AVB/TSN can handle rate-constrained traffic, where each stream has a bandwidth limit defined by minimum inter-frame intervals and maximal frame size, and time-trigger traffic with an exact accurate time to be sent.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Low-priority traffic is passed on a best-effort basis, with no timing and delivery guarantees.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] In contrast to standard Ethernet according to IEEE 802.3 and Ethernet bridging according to IEEE 802.1Q, time is very important in TSN networks.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] For real-time communication with hard, non-negotiable time boundaries for end-to-end transmission latencies, all devices in this network need to have a common time reference and therefore, need to synchronize their clocks among each other.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] This is not only true for the end devices of a communication stream, such as an industrial controller and a manufacturing robot, but also true for network components, such as Ethernet switches.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Only through synchronized clocks is it possible for all network devices to operate in unison and execute the required operation at exactly the required point in time.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Although time synchronization in TSN networks can be achieved with GPS clock, this is costly and there is no guarantee that the endpoint device has access to the radio or satellite signal at all times.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Due to these constraints, time in TSN networks is usually distributed from one central time source directly through the network itself using the IEEE 1588 Precision Time Protocol, which utilizes Ethernet frames to distribute time synchronization information.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1AS is a tightly constrained subset of IEEE 1588 with sub-microsecond precision and extensions to support synchronisation over WiFi radio (IEEE 802.11).
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The idea behind this profile is to narrow the huge list of different IEEE 1588 options down to a manageable few critical options that are applicable to home networks or networks in automotive or industrial automation environments.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1AS-2011 defines the Generalized Precision Time Protocol (gPTP) profile which, like all profiles of IEEE 1588, selects among the options of 1588, but also generalizes the architecture to allow PTP to apply beyond wired Ethernet networks.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] These calculated delays are then referenced to the GrandMaster (GM) clock in a bridge elected by the Best Master Clock Algorithm, a clock Spanning Tree Protocol to which all Clock Master (CM) and endpoint devices attempt to synchronize.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Any device that does not synchronize to timing messages is outside of the timing domain boundaries (Figure 2).
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Synchronization accuracy depends on precise measurements of link delay and frame residence time.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] 802.1AS uses *logical syntonization*, where a ratio between local clock and GM clock frequencies is used to calculate synchronized time, and a ratio between local and GM clock frequencies to calculate propagation delay.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE802.1AS-2020 introduces improved time measurement accuracy and support for multiple time domains for redundancy.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Scheduling and traffic shaping allow for the coexistence of different traffic classes with different priorities on the same network – each with different requirements for available bandwidth and end-to-end latency.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Traffic shaping refers to the process of distributing frames/packets evenly in time to smooth out the traffic.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Without traffic shaping at sources and bridges, the packets will *bunch*, i.e., agglomerate into bursts of traffic, overwhelming the buffers in subsequent bridges/switches along the path.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Standard bridging according to IEEE 802.1Q uses a strict priority scheme with eight distinct priorities.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] On the protocol level, these priorities are visible in the Priority Code Point (PCP) field in the 802.1Q VLAN tag of a standard Ethernet frame.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] These priorities already distinguish between more important and less important network traffic, but even with the highest of the eight priorities, no absolute guarantee for an end-to-end delivery time can be given.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The reason for this is buffering effects inside the Ethernet switches.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] If a switch has started the transmission of an Ethernet frame on one of its ports, even the highest-priority frame has to wait inside the switch buffer for this transmission to finish.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] With standard Ethernet switching, this nondeterminism cannot be avoided.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] This is not an issue in environments where applications do not depend on the timely delivery of single Ethernet frames - such as office IT infrastructures.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] In these environments, file transfers, emails or other business applications have limited time sensitivity themselves and are usually protected by other mechanisms further up the protocol stack, such as the Transmission Control Protocol.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] In industrial automation (Programmable Logic Controller (PLC) with an industrial robot) and automotive car environments, where closed loop control or safety applications are using the Ethernet network, reliable and timely delivery is of utmost importance.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] AVB/TSN enhances standard Ethernet communication by adding mechanisms to provide different time slices for different traffic classes and ensure timely delivery with soft and hard real-time requirements of control system applications.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The mechanism of utilizing the eight distinct VLAN priorities is retained, to ensure complete backward compatibility to non-TSN Ethernet.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Time-sensitive traffic has several priority classes.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] For credit-based shaper 802.1Qav, Stream Reservation Class A is the highest priority with a transmission period of 125 μs; Class B has the second-highest priority with a maximum transmission period of 250 μs.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Traffic classes shall not exceed their preconfigured maximum bandwidth (75% for audio and video applications).
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The worst-case latency requirement is defined as 2 ms for Class A and 50 ms for Class B, but has been shown to be unreliable.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The per-port peer delay provided by gPTP and the network bridge residence delay are added to calculate the accumulated delays and ensure the latency requirement is met.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Control traffic has the third-highest priority and includes gPTP and SRP traffic.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Time-aware scheduler 802.1Qbv introduces Class CDT for real-time control data from sensors and command streams to actuators, with worst-case latency of 100 μs over 5 hops, and a maximum transmission period of 0.5 ms.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Class CDT takes the highest priority over classes A, B, and control traffic.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1Qav Forwarding and Queuing Enhancements for Time-Sensitive Streams defines traffic shaping using priority classes, which is based on a simple form of leaky bucket credit-based fair queuing.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] 802.1Qav is designed to reduce buffering in receiving bridges and endpoints.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The credit-based shaper defines credits in bits for two separate queues, dedicated to Class A and Class B traffic.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Thus the idleSlope is the bandwidth reserved for the queue by the bridge, and the sendSlope is the transmission rate of the port MAC service.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] If the credit is negative and no frames are transmitted, credit increases at *idleSlope* rate until zero is reached.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] If an AVB frame cannot be transmitted because a non-AVB frame is in transmission, credit accumulates at *idleSlope* rate, but positive credit is allowed.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Additional limits hiCredit and loCredit are derived from the maximum frame size and maximum interference size, the idleSlope/sendSlope, and the maximum port transmission rate.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Reserved AV stream traffic frames are forwarded with high priority over non-reserved best-effort traffic, subject to credit-based traffic shaping rules which may require them to wait for a certain amount of credits.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] This protects best-effort traffic by limiting the maximum AV stream burst.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The frames are scheduled very evenly, though only on an aggregate basis, to smooth out the delivery times and reduce bursting and bunching, which can lead to buffer overflows and packet drops that trigger retransmissions.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The increased buffering delay makes re-transmitted packets obsolete by the time they arrive, resulting in frame drops, which reduces the quality of AV applications.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Deriving guaranteed upper bounds on delays in TSN is non-trivial and is currently being researched, e.g., by using the mathematical framework Network Calculus.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1Qat Stream Reservation Protocol (SRP) is a distributed peer-to-peer protocol that specifies admission controls based on resource requirements of the flow and available network resources.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] SRP reserves resources and advertises streams from the sender/source (talker) to the receivers/destinations (listeners); it works to satisfy QoS requirements for each stream and guarantee the availability of sufficient network resources along the entire flow transmission path.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The traffic streams are identified and registered with a 64-bit *StreamID*, made up of the 48-bit MAC address (EUI) and 16-bit *UniqueID* to identify different streams from the same source.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] SRP employs variants of Multiple Registration Protocol (MRP) to register and de-register attribute values on switches/bridges/devices - the Multiple MAC Registration Protocol (MMRP), the Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol (MVRP), and the Multiple Stream Registration Protocol (MSRP).
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Resources are allocated and configured in both the end nodes of the data stream and the transit nodes along the data flow path, with an end-to-end signaling mechanism to detect the success/failure.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Worst-case latency is calculated by querying every bridge.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Reservation requests use the general MRP application with the MRP attribute propagation mechanism.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] All nodes along the flow path pass the MRP Attribute Declaration (MAD) specification, which describes the stream characteristics so that bridges could allocate the necessary resources.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] If a bridge is able to reserve the required resources, it propagates the advertisement to the next bridge; otherwise, a *talker failed* message is raised.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] When the advertisement message reaches the listener, it replies with *listener ready* message that propagates back to the talker.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Successful reservation is only guaranteed when all intermediate nodes support SRP and respond to advertise and ready messages; in Figure 2 above, AVB domain 1 is unable to connect with AVB domain 2.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] SRP uses a decentralized registration and reservation procedure; multiple requests can introduce delays for critical traffic.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1Qcc-2018 "Stream Reservation Protocol (SRP) Enhancements and Performance Improvements" amendment reduces the size of reservation messages and redefines timers so they trigger updates only when link state or reservation is changed.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] CNC implements a per-stream request-response model, where SR class is not explicitly used: end-stations send requests for a specific stream (via edge port) without knowledge of the network configuration, and CNC performs stream reservation centrally.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] MSRP only runs on the link to end-stations as an information carrier between CNC and end-stations, not for stream reservation.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Centralized User Configuration (CUC) is an optional node that discovers end stations, their capabilities and user requirements, and configures delay-optimized TSN features (for closed-loop IACS applications).
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Seamless interop with Resource Reservation Protocol (RSVP) transport is provided.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] 802.1Qcc allows centralized configuration management to coexist with decentralized, fully distributed configuration of the SRP protocol, and also supports hybrid configurations for legacy AVB devices.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] 802.1Qcc can be combined with IEEE 802.1Qca Path Control and Reservation (PCR) and TSN traffic shapers.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] While the 802.1Qav FQTSS/CBS works very well with soft real-time traffic, worst-case delays are both hop count and network topology dependent.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Pathological topologies introduce delays, so buffer size requirements have to consider network topology.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] CQF can be used with the IEEE 802.1Qbv time-aware scheduler, IEEE 802.1Qbu frame preemption, and IEEE 802.1Qci ingress traffic policing.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1Qci Per-Stream Filtering and Policing (PSFP) improves network robustness by filtering individual traffic streams.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] It prevents traffic overload conditions that may affect bridges and the receiving endpoints due to malfunction or Denial of Service (DoS) attacks.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The stream filter uses rule matching to allow frames with specified stream IDs and priority levels and apply policy actions otherwise.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] All streams are coordinated at their gates, similarly to the 802.1Qch signaling.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The flow metering applies predefined bandwidth profiles for each stream.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The IEEE 802.1Qbv time-aware scheduler is designed to separate the communication on the Ethernet network into fixed length, repeating time cycles.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Within these cycles, different time slices can be configured that can be assigned to one or several of the eight Ethernet priorities.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] By doing this, it is possible to grant exclusive use - for a limited time - to the Ethernet transmission medium for those traffic classes that need transmission guarantees and can't be interrupted.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The basic concept is a time-division multiple access (TDMA) scheme.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] By establishing virtual communication channels for specific time periods, time-critical communication can be separated from non-critical background traffic.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Time-aware scheduler introduces Stream Reservation Class CDT for time-critical control data, with worst-case latency of 100 μs over 5 hops, and maximum transmission period of 0.5 ms, in addition to classes A and B defined for IEEE 802.1Qav credit-based traffic shaper.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] By granting exclusive access to the transmission medium and devices to time-critical traffic classes, the buffering effects in the Ethernet switch transmission buffers can be avoided and time-critical traffic can be transmitted without non-deterministic interruptions.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] In this example, each cycle consists of two time slices.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Time slice 1 only allows the transmission of traffic tagged with VLAN priority 3, and time slice 2 in each cycle allows for the rest of the priorities to be sent.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Since the IEEE 802.1Qbv scheduler requires all clocks on all network devices (Ethernet switches and end devices) to be synchronized and the identical schedule to be configured, all devices understand which priority can be sent to the network at any given point in time.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Since time slice 2 has more than one priority assigned to it, within this time slice, the priorities are handled according to standard IEEE 802.1Q strict priority scheduling.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] This separation of Ethernet transmissions into cycles and time slices can be enhanced further by the inclusion of other scheduling or traffic shaping algorithms, such as the IEEE 802.1Qav credit-based traffic shaper.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] In this particular example, IEEE 802.1Qav could be assigned to one or two of the priorities that are used in time slice two to distinguish further between audio/video traffic and background file transfers.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The Time-Sensitive Networking Task Group specifies a number of different schedulers and traffic shapers that can be combined to achieve the nonreactive coexistence of hard real-time, soft real-time and background traffic on the same Ethernet infrastructure.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] When an Ethernet interface has started the transmission of a frame to the transmission medium, this transmission has to be completely finished before another transmission can take place.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] This includes the transmission of the CRC-32 checksum at the end of the frame to ensure a reliable, fault-free transmission.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] This inherent property of Ethernet networks - again- poses a challenge to the TDMA approach of the IEEE 802.1Qbv scheduler.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Just before the end of time slice 2 in cycle n, a new frame transmission is started.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Unfortunately, this frame is too large to fit into its time slice.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Since the transmission of this frame cannot be interrupted, the frame infringes the following time slice 1 of the next cycle n+1.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] By partially or completely blocking a time-critical time slice, real-time frames can be delayed up to the point where they cannot meet the application requirements any longer.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] This is very similar to the actual buffering effects that happen in non-TSN Ethernet switches, so TSN has to specify a mechanism to prevent this from happening.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The IEEE 802.1Qbv time-aware scheduler has to ensure that the Ethernet interface is not busy with the transmission of a frame when the scheduler changes from one time slice to the next.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The time-aware scheduler achieves this by putting a guard band in front of every time slice that carries time-critical traffic.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] During this guard band time, no new Ethernet frame transmission may be started; only already ongoing transmissions may be finished.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The duration of this guard band has to be as long as it takes the maximum frame size to be safely transmitted.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The total time needed for sending this frame is dependent on the link speed of the Ethernet network.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] In this case, the guard band has to be at least 123.36 μs long.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] With the guard band, the total bandwidth or time that is usable within a time slice is reduced by the length of the guard band.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Note: to facilitate the presentation of the topic, the actual size of the guard band in figure 3 is not to scale, but is significantly smaller than indicated by the frame in figure 2.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] In this example, the time slice 1 always contains high-priority data (e.g. for motion control), while time slice 2 always contains best-effort data.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Therefore, a guard band needs to be placed at every transition point into time slice 1 to protect the time slice of the critical data stream(s).
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] To partially mitigate the loss of bandwidth through the guard band, the standard IEEE 802.1Qbv includes a length-aware scheduling mechanism.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] This mechanism is used when store-and-forward switching is utilized: after the full reception of an Ethernet frame that needs to be transmitted on a port where the guard band is in effect, the scheduler checks the overall length of the frame.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] If the frame can fit completely inside the guard band, without any infringement of the following high-priority slice, the scheduler can send this frame, despite an active guard band, and reduce the waste of bandwidth.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] This mechanism, however, cannot be used when cut-through switching is enabled, since the total length of the Ethernet frame needs to be known a priori.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Therefore, when cut-through switching is used to minimize end-to-end latency, the waste of bandwidth will still occur.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Also, this does not help with the minimum achievable cycle time.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Therefore, length-aware scheduling is an improvement, but cannot mitigate all drawbacks that are introduced by the guard band.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] To further mitigate the negative effects of the guard bands, the IEEE working groups 802.1 and 802.3 have specified the frame pre-emption technology.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The two working groups collaborated in this endeavour since the technology required both changes in the Ethernet Media Access Control (MAC) scheme that is under the control of IEEE 802.3, as well as changes in the management mechanisms that are under the control of IEEE 802.1.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Due to this fact, frame pre-emption is described in two different standards documents: IEEE 802.1Qbu for the bridge management component and IEEE 802.3br for the Ethernet MAC component.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Frame preemption defines two MAC services for an egress port: preemptable MAC (pMAC) and express MAC (eMAC).
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Express frames can interrupt the transmission of preemptable frames.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] On resume, MAC merge sublayer reassembles frame fragments in the next bridge.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Preemption causes computational overhead in the link interface, as the operational context shall be transitioned to the express frame.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Figure 4 gives a basic example how frame pre-emption works.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] During the process of sending a best effort Ethernet frame, the MAC interrupts the frame transmission just before the start of the guard band.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The partial frame is completed with a CRC and will be stored in the next switch to wait for the second part of the frame to arrive.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] After the high-priority traffic in time slice 1 has passed and the cycle switches back to time slice 2, the interrupted frame transmission is resumed.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Frame pre-emption always operates on a pure link-by-link basis and only fragments from one Ethernet switch to the next Ethernet switch, where the frame is reassembled.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] In contrast to fragmentation with the Internet Protocol (IP), no end-to-end fragmentation is supported.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Each partial frame is completed by a CRC-32 for error detection.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] In contrast to the regular Ethernet CRC-32, the last 16 bits are inverted to make a partial frame distinguishable from a regular Ethernet frame.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] In addition, the start of frame delimiter (SFD) is changed.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The support for frame pre-emption has to be activated on each link between devices individually.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] To signal the capability for frame pre-emption on a link, an Ethernet switch announces this capability through the LLDP (Link Layer Discovery Protocol).
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] When a device receives such an LLDP announcement on a network port and supports frame pre-emption itself, it may activate the capability.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] There is no direct negotiation and activation of the capability on adjacent devices.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Any device that receives the LLDP pre-emption announcement assumes that on the other end of the link, a device is present that can understand the changes in the frame format (changed CRC-32 and SFD).
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Frame pre-emption allows for a significant reduction of the guard band.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The length of the guard band is now dependent on the precision of the frame pre-emption mechanism: how small is the minimum size of the frame that the mechanism can still preempt.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.3br specifies the best accuracy for this mechanism at 64 bytes – due to the fact that this is the minimum size of a still valid Ethernet frame.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] In this case, the guard band can be reduced to a total of 127 bytes: 64 bytes (minimum frame) + 63 bytes (remaining length that cannot be pre-empted).
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] All larger frames can be pre-empted again and therefore, there is no need to protect against this size with a guard band.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] This minimizes the best effort bandwidth that is lost and also allows for much shorter cycle times at slower Ethernet speeds, such as 100 Mbit/s and below.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Since the pre-emption takes place in hardware in the MAC, as the frame passes through, cut-through switching can be supported as well, since the overall frame size is not needed a priori.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The MAC interface just checks in regular 64-byte intervals whether the frame needs to be preempted or not.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The combination of time synchronization, the IEEE 802.1Qbv scheduler and frame pre-emption already constitutes an effective set of standards that can be utilized to guarantee the coexistence of different traffic categories on a network while also providing end-to-end latency guarantees.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] This will be enhanced further as new IEEE 802.1 specifications, such as 802.1Qch are finalized.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Overall, the time-aware scheduler has high implementation complexity and its use of bandwidth is not efficient.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Task and event scheduling in endpoints has to be coupled with the gate scheduling of the traffic shaper in order to lower the latencies.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] A critical shortcoming is that some delay is incurred when an endpoint streams unsynchronized data, due to the waiting time for the next time-triggered window.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The time-aware scheduler requires tight synchronization of its time-triggered windows, so all bridges on the stream path must be synchronized.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] However, synchronizing TSN bridge frame selection and transmission time is nontrivial even in moderately sized networks and requires a fully managed solution.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Frame preemption is hard to implement and has not seen wide industry support.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Credit-based, time-aware and cyclic (peristaltic) shapers require network-wide coordinated time and utilize network bandwidth inefficiently, as they enforce packet transmission at periodic cycles.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The IEEE 802.1Qcr Asynchronous Traffic Shaper (ATS) operates asynchronously based on local clocks in each bridge, improving link utilization for mixed traffic types, such as periodic with arbitrary periods, sporadic (event driven), and rate-constrained.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] ATS employs the urgency-based scheduler (UBS), which prioritizes urgent traffic using per-class queuing and per-stream reshaping.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Asynchronicity is achieved by interleaved shaping with traffic characterization based on Token Bucket Emulation, a token bucket emulation model, to eliminate the burstiness cascade effects of per-class shaping.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The TBE shaper controls the traffic by average transmission rate, but allows a certain level of burst traffic.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] When there is a sufficient number of tokens in the bucket, transmission starts immediately; otherwise, the queue's gate closes for the time needed to accumulate enough tokens.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] This separation of queuing has low implementation complexity while ensuring that frames with higher priority will bypass the lower priority frames.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The shared queues are highly isolated, with policies for separate queues for frames from different transmitters, the same transmitter but different priority, and the same transmitter and priority but a different priority at the receiver.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Queue isolation prevents propagation of malicious data, assuring that ordinary streams will get no interference, and enables flexible stream or transmitter blocking by administrative action.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The minimum number of shared queues is the number of ports minus one, and more with additional isolation policies.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Shared queues have scheduler internal fixed priority, and frames are transmitted on the First Come First Serve principle.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Worst-case clock sync inaccuracy does not decrease link utilization, contrary to time-triggered approaches such as TAS (Qbv) and CQF (Qch).
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1Qca Path Control and Reservation (PCR) specifies extensions to the Intermediate Station to Intermediate Station (IS-IS) protocol to configure multiple paths in bridged networks.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The IEEE 802.1Qca standard uses Shortest Path Bridging (SPB) with a software-defined networking (SDN) hybrid mode - the IS-IS protocol handles basic functions, while the SDN controller manages explicit paths using Path Computation Elements (PCEs) at dedicated server nodes.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1Qca integrates control protocols to manage multiple topologies, configure an explicit forwarding path (a predefined path for each stream), reserve bandwidth, provides data protection and redundancy, and distribute flow synchronization and flow control messages.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] These are derived from Equal Cost Tree (ECT), Multiple Spanning Tree Instance (MSTI) and Internal Spanning Tree (IST), and Explicit Tree (ET) protocols.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE 802.1CB Frame Replication and Elimination for Reliability (FRER) sends duplicate copies of each frame over multiple disjoint paths to provide proactive seamless redundancy for control applications that cannot tolerate packet losses.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The packet replication can use traffic class and path information to minimize network congestion.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Each replicated frame has a sequence identification number, used to re-order and merge frames and to discard duplicates.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] FRER requires centralized configuration management and needs to be used with 802.1Qcc and 802.1Qca.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Industrial fault-tolerance HSR and PRP specified in IEC 62439-3 are supported.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] MRP state data for a stream takes 1500 bytes.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] With additional traffic streams and larger networks, the size of the database proportionally increases and MRP updates between bridge neighbors significantly slow down.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The Link-Local Registration Protocol (LRP) is optimized for a larger database size of about 1 Mbyte with efficient replication that allows incremental updates.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Unresponsive nodes with stale data are automatically discarded.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] While MRP is application specific, with each registered application defining its own set of operations, LRP is application neutral.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE P802.1Qdd project updates the distributed configuration model by defining new peer-to-peer Resource Allocation Protocol signaling built upon P802.1CS Link-local Registration Protocol.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] RAP will improve scalability and provide dynamic reservation for a larger number of streams with support for redundant transmission over multiple paths in 802.1CB FRER, and autoconfiguration of sequence recovery.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] RAP supports the 'topology-independent per-hop latency calculation' capability of TSN shapers such as 802.1Qch Cyclic Queuing and Forwarding (CQF) and P802.1Qcr Asynchronous Traffic Shaping (ATS).
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] It will also improve performance under high load and support proxying and enhanced diagnostics, all while maintaining backward compatibility and interoperability with MSRP.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] IEEE P802.1ABdh Station and Media Access Control Connectivity Discovery - Support for Multiframe Protocol Data Units (LLDPv2) updates LLDP to support IETF Link State Vector Routing protocol and improve efficiency of protocol messages.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] YANG is a Unified Modeling Language (UML) for configuration and state data, notifications, and remote procedure calls, to set up device configuration with network management protocols such as NETCONF/RESTCONF.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The IETF Deterministic Networking (DetNet) Working Group is focusing on defining deterministic data paths with high reliability and bounds on latency, loss, and packet delay variation (jitter), such as audio and video streaming, industrial automation, and vehicle control.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The goals of Deterministic Networking are to migrate time-critical, high-reliability industrial and audio-video applications from special-purpose Fieldbus networks to IP packet networks.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] To achieve these goals, DetNet uses resource allocation to manage buffer sizes and transmission rates in order to satisfy end-to-end latency requirements.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Service protection against failures with redundancy over multiple paths and explicit routes to reduce packet loss and reordering.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] The same physical network shall handle both time-critical reserved traffic and regular best-effort traffic, and unused reserved bandwidth shall be released for best-effort traffic.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] DetNet operates at the IP Layer 3 routed segments using a software-defined networking layer to provide IntServ and DiffServ integration, and delivers services over lower Layer 2 bridged segments using technologies such as MPLS and IEEE 802.1 AVB/TSN.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] Also, the protocol interworking defined by IEEE 802.1CB is used to advertise TSN sub-network capabilities to DetNet flows via the Active Destination MAC and VLAN Stream identification functions.
[src:automotive-ethernet/time-sensitive-networking] DetNet flows are matched by destination MAC address, VLAN ID and priority parameters to Stream ID and QoS requirements for talkers and listeners in the AVB/TSN sub-network.
